"Abstract The poor and indigent (or should I say indignant?) relation of computer security, disaster recovery has been creeping up in importance over the past ten years, but still not to the same extent as its more newsworthy siblings. Originally concerned with saving our systems from the tempestuous vagaries of extreme weather conditions, who could blame those of us living in the moderate climes of Western Europe — never having to worry about anything more than a bit of heavy rain — putting disaster recovery on the back burner? With all that rain, there was never enough to make a flood (well, not until the rain forests started disappearing in earnest). When we read about businesses recovering from hurricanes, volcanoes, typhoons, tornadoes, avalanches and earthquakes, it was more out of casual interest than learned curiosity, I mean, Ireland and the UK just don’t experience these climatic phenomena. But now weather is the least of our worries."
